Magma storage and migration associated with the 2011–2012 El Hierro eruption: Implications for crustal magmatic systems at oceanic island volcanoes

Pablo J. González, 
Corresponding author: P. J. González, Department of Earth Sciences, University of Western Ontario, Biological and Geological Sciences Building, 1151 Richmond St. London, ON N6A 5B7, Canada. ()

Abstract

[1] Starting in July 2011, anomalous seismicity was observed at El Hierro Island, a young oceanic island volcano. On 12 October 2011, the process led to the beginning of a submarine NW-SE fissural eruption at ~15 km from the initial earthquake loci, indicative of significant lateral magma migration. Here we conduct a multifrequency, multisensor interferometric analysis of spaceborne radar images acquired using three different satellite systems (RADARSAT-2, ENVISAT, and COSMO-SkyMed (Constellation of Small Satellites for Mediterranean Basin Observation)). The data fully captures both the pre-eruptive and coeruptive phases. Elastic modeling of the ground deformation is employed to constrain the dynamics associated with the magmatic activity. This study represents the first geodetically constrained active magmatic plumbing system model for any of the Canary Islands volcanoes, and one of the few examples of submarine volcanic activity to date. Geodetic results reveal two spatially distinct shallow (crustal) magma reservoirs, a deeper central source (9.5 ± 4.0 km), and a shallower magma reservoir at the flank of the southern rift (4.5 ± 2.0 km). The deeper source was recharged, explaining the relatively long basaltic eruption, contributing to the observed island-wide uplift processes, and validating proposed active magma underplating. The shallowest source may be an incipient reservoir that facilitates fractional crystallization as observed at other Canary Islands. Data from this eruption supports a relationship between the depth of the shallow crustal magmatic systems and the long-term magma supply rate and oceanic lithospheric age. Such a relationship implies that a factor controlling the existence/depth of shallow (crustal) magmatic systems in oceanic island volcanoes is the lithosphere thermomechanical behavior.

Key Points

  • Inverse modeling method for source temporal evolution combining data sets
  • Active crustal magmatic system with two levels during El Hierro eruption
  • Depth of crustal magmatic chambers depends on lithosphere thermomechanics

1 Introduction

[2] A deeper understanding of the magma plumbing system is critical to our ability to forecast the eruptive behavior of a volcano and to provide a wider framework to constrain dynamic volcanic processes, such as magma storage, supply rate, and migration [Takada, 1989; Poland et al., 2012; Clague and Dixon, 2000, Fialko and Rubin, 1998]. Attempts to understand the structure and dynamics of magma plumbing systems at basaltic intraplate oceanic island volcanoes rely heavily on a handful of well-studied volcanoes, e.g., Kilauea and Piton de la Fournaise [Tilling and Dvorak, 1993]. However, the lack of data at other volcanoes makes it difficult to extrapolate a well-constrained magma plumbing systems and dynamics that may be used as prototypes for all oceanic island volcanoes. In particular, less active volcanoes such as the Canary or Cape Verde Islands might not be described accurately by plumbing systems inferred from highly active volcanoes.

[3] An image of the active magmatic plumbing system of a volcano can be obtained via the interpretation of various geological, geophysical, and geochemical data, including seismic, experimental petrology, gas emissions chemistry, and geodetic measurements [Dzurisin, 2006]. To study the long-term evolution of magmatic systems, experimental petrology provides a very valuable tool through the analysis of erupted materials [Marsh, 1996; Hansteen et al., 1998; Longpré et al., 2008]. However, at active volcanic areas, geophysical observations are an important complement, providing constraints on magma locations and volumes. Geodetic imaging is useful to infer complex deformation processes controlled by crustal rheology. In volcanic environments, the temperature and density contrasts affect the stress distribution which controls the dynamic magmatic processes. Nonetheless, under certain assumptions (usually brittle/elastic deformation), it is possible to evaluate magma volume storage and migration beneath a volcano [Dzurisin, 2006; Poland et al., 2012]. Therefore, the ground deformation associated with an eruption allows us to constrain the magma plumbing systems, in particular at basaltic intraplate oceanic island volcanoes with low eruption rates, and compare its structure and dynamics against the prototypes.

[4] Studies of the magma plumbing systems at basaltic intraplate ocean island volcanoes (e.g., Reunion, Galápagos, Hawaiian, Canarian, and Cape Verde Islands) have revealed fundamental differences in their shallower (crustal) levels. It has been postulated that shallow (crustal) magma chambers are not always present and differ in magmatic processes. At Hawaii, magma chambers stagnate and distribute magma along elongated rift zones [Tilling and Dvorak, 1993]. However, at Tenerife and Gran Canaria Islands, crustal magma chambers develop as long-lived features that can fractionate parental basanitic composition melts into end-member (highly explosive) phonolitic magmas [Ablay and Martí, 2000]. Nevertheless, multiple processes such as flank instability also can play a role in the absence/presence of magma reservoirs by occasionally disrupting the volcanic plumbing system [e.g., Amelung and Day, 2002; Ruch et al., 2012]. Therefore, a deeper understanding of the crustal portion of the plumbing systems of oceanic island volcanoes is essential for improving volcanic risk analysis.

[5] A submarine eruption off El Hierro Island started in October 2011 and ended in early March 2012 [López et al., 2012]. The 2011–2012 El Hierro eruption represents the first eruptive episode in 40 years and the first systematically well-monitored eruption in the Canary Islands. Consequently, the analysis of data acquired during the 2011–2012 El Hierro eruption is a unique opportunity to image, for the first time, the active magmatic system of one of the Canary Islands. In addition, it provides the first opportunity to study the volcanic phenomena associated with an onshore to offshore migration of magma that culminated into an eruption. This study also contributes to our knowledge of the magmatic systems of oceanic island volcanoes.

2 El Hierro Island and the 2011–2012 Eruption

[6] El Hierro Island is small basaltic oceanic island volcano with a subaerial edifice ~20 km in diameter and steep relief, with maximum altitudes of 1500 m (Pico de Malpaso) above the surrounding seafloor and bathymetry of approximately 3600–3800 m. Located in the Canary Islands volcanic archipelago, off the African continent (Figure 1), El Hierro is the south-westernmost and the youngest island, at 1.1 Ma old [Carracedo et al., 2001]. Geologically, El Hierro is composed of three overlapping units (Tiñor, El Golfo, and rift volcanism) which have suffered four flank collapses [Masson et al., 2002; Muenn et al., 2006]. The oldest formation is the Tiñor shield volcano, with activity spanning 1.2–0.88 Ma. It has been inferred that this volcano collapsed northward. Later, another shield volcano, El Golfo, completely covered the Tiñor collapse [Carracedo et al., 2001]. Eventually, El Golfo volcano again collapsed toward the north, forming the El Golfo flank collapse (87–39 ka), a prominent embayment in the north (Figure 1) [Longpré et al., 2011]. Over the last 158 ka, volcanism has been presented as effusive along three major rift zones (northeastern, west-northwestern, and southern), with the development of strombolian cinder cones and associated lava flows (Figure 1). At El Hierro, Holocene volcanism is limited to a few dated eruptions; Tanganasoga volcano, a composite volcano that erupted crystal-rich ankaramite lavas, and the Montaña Chamuscada volcano, 4000 and 2500 years before present, respectively [Guillou et al., 1996; Manconi et al., 2009]. For the last 500 years, which corresponds with the historical record, no volcanic eruptions have been confirmed. In 1793, a felt seismic crisis was dubiously associated with the eruption of the Lomo Negro volcano, northwest of the island [Carracedo et al., 2001; Romero and Guillén, 2012]. Over the past decade, seismicity has remained low, with an average seismicity rate of <10 earthquakes/year. In 2004, a minor increase in seismic activity was correlated with a simultaneous increment in CO2 soil diffuse efflux [Padrón et al., 2008].

[7] On 17 July 2011, the two permanent seismic stations of the Spanish Geographical Survey, IGN [www.ign.es], detected unusual activity (Figure 2). From 17 July 2011 to early September, small magnitude seismicity, mbLg < 3 (Figures 3a and 3b), occurred in small clusters at a depth range from 9 to 15 km and varying slightly in position beneath the Tanganasoga volcano area (see Figures 1, 2, and 3a–3c). At the initial stage in late July, seismicity migrated generally toward the west (Figure 3a). This trend shifted slightly toward the northwest in early to mid-August (Figure 3b). By mid-August, activity returned to the initial area (dark circles in Figure 3b) and remained stationary for next the 15 days or so. Only one publicly available GPS station (FRON) was operating prior to the onset of the seismic swarm, located in an area northeast of the located epicenters in El Golfo collapse valley (Figure 1). By the end of August, the GPS precise positioning indicated a cumulative uplift of ~4 and ~2 cm motion toward the northeast. In mid-September 2011, the seismicity began to migrate clearly southward. Simultaneously, the magnitude of events increased, and earthquakes began to be strongly felt by the population, mbLg ~ 3–4 (Figure 3c). In late September to early October, the seismicity clearly stopped its southward migration and spread around a wide area, ~5 km in diameter, beneath the Mar de las Calmas (Figures 1, 3c, and 3d).

[8] An energetic seismic swarm began late on 5 October 2011, peaking at a maximum mbLg = 4.4 (Mw = 4.0) on 8 October 2011 at 20:35 UTC, with a moment tensor and centroid at 6 km depth [www.ign.es accessed 27 March 2012]. It was followed by a relatively quiet period of ~32 h, during which a few tens of low-magnitude shallow events were located at depths of 1 to 6 km. This period ended with the emergence of a growing amplitude tremor signal (10 October 2012, ~4:15 UTC). The tremor amplitude increased for ~24 h, including clipping of some seismometers [www.ign.es]. The tremor signal abruptly ceased after a peak in high frequency at 14:30 UTC on 12 October 2011, followed by several high frequency peaks during the next ~24 h. On 15 October 2011, the first floating material began to appear off the coast near La Restinga town (Figure 1). The material varied from a mixture of mafic and white pumice to large basanite floating balloons [Troll et al., 2012; Carracedo et al., 2012]. Between 9 and 26 October 2011, the submarine eruption continued to be associated with very minor seismicity (a few earthquakes/day) and the magnitudes remained low, mbLg < 3 (Figures 2c and 3d). Subsequently, very deep seismicity (20–30 km) appeared along the northern coast (El Golfo), accompanied by visible changes at the eruption site such as volcanic bombs and bubbling associated with vigorous degassing (Figures 3d and 2e). For the next 3 months, eruptive seismicity was sparse and without clear patterns in either space or time (Figure 3f). While visible sea surface discoloration disappeared in late December, by early January, basaltic floating bombs reappeared and continued throughout February in a discontinuous fashion. In early March, the absence of visible effects on the sea surface and the lower levels of seismicity triggered official declaration of the end of the eruption on 5 March 2012 [www.gobiernodecanarias.org/dgse/noticias_sismo_hierro.html]. A more complete comprehensive qualitative description of the chronology of the crisis can be found in Carracedo et al. [2012] and López et al. [2012].

[9] Prior to July 2011, the geodetic monitoring of El Hierro Island was composed of two GPS stations managed by different institutions. GRAFCAN (Cartográfica de Canarias) managed one located in El Golfo valley with open data access (Frontera, FRON station) that was installed in 2010 for surveying purposes. A second station was installed in 2004 by ITER-INVOLCAN (Instituto Tecnológico y Energías Renovables-Instituto Volcanológico de Canarias) in cooperation with Nagoya University [González et al., 2006]. During August 2011, this minimal network was augmented with five well-distributed GPS stations by INVOLCAN [Sagiya et al., 2012]. Meanwhile, the Spanish IGN installed four GPS stations along a single transect in El Golfo area [López et al., 2012]. Although this GPS profile distribution provided some information with which to constrain depth and source geometry, it is not optimized to track the location (and migration) of deformation sources due to its small aperture and the narrow back azimuths of the displacement GPS vectors. The addition of five continuous GPS and three survey GPS benchmarks in late September 2011 provided improved coverage of the entire island. In addition to the GPS networks, tiltmeter and microgravity networks were installed to monitor ground deformation and gravity changes [Arnoso et al., 2012]. Here we complement the ground-based geodetic network with comprehensive processing, analysis, and modeling of multiple space-based radar interferometric data sets (RADARSAT-2, ASAR-ENVISAT, and COSMO-SkyMed (Constellation of Small Satellites for Mediterranean Basin Observation)) in order to understand the dynamics of the magmatic system.

3 Data Analysis: Interferometric Synthetic Aperture Radar (InSAR) Observations

[10] Interferometric Synthetic Aperture Radar (InSAR) is a geodetic technique that measures surface ground deformation between two different satellite passes over wide areas [e.g., Dzurisin, 2006; Sansosti et al., 2010]. InSAR measurements are sensitive to a projection of the full 3-D displacement vector onto the satellite line of sight (LOS). Ideally, it is desirable to image the area of interest with more than one satellite track (ascending and descending passes, with variable incidence angles) in order to measure more than one projection of the full displacement vector and, therefore, to better constrain models representing geophysical processes.

[11] We used 32 SAR images from six different satellite tracks to image the ground deformation at El Hierro Island. SAR images were acquired between December 2009 and March 2012 (Table S1). Images were acquired from two ascending tracks of the Canadian Space Agency RADARSAT-2 satellite, beams S6 (look angle, 44°) and S7 (47°); and two descending tracks of the European Space Agency (ESA) ENVISAT satellite, tracks 109 in I6 mode (36°) and 339 in I2 mode (20°). RADARSAT-2 and ENVISAT satellites are equipped with right-looking C-band SAR antennas operating at wavelength of ~5.6 cm. In addition, images were acquired from ascending and descending tracks of the Italian Space Agency (ASI) COSMO-SkyMed satellite, both corresponding to the beam H4-8 (34°). The latter system is an advanced X-band SAR constellation with four satellites operating at a wavelength of ~3.1 cm.

[12] Interferograms were processed in two-pass differential mode, using a 30 m resolution digital elevation model (DEM) derived from the Shuttle Radar Topography Mission, and a 5 m resolution DEM from IGN to remove topographic effects from C-band and X-band SAR data, respectively. ENVISAT-ASAR data were processed using Doris software [Kampes et al., 2003], RADARSAT-2 data were processed using GAMMA software [Wegmuller and Werner, 1997], COSMO-SkyMed data were processed at National Research Council-Istituto per il Rilevamento Elettromagnetico dell'Ambiente (CNR-IREA) using their internally developed interferometric SAR processing chain [Berardino et al., 2002]. Overall, we obtained 63 short baseline differential interferograms (Table S2). Computed interferograms have temporal separations ranging from 3 days to approximately 2 years.

[13] El Hierro Island presented some challenges for InSAR analysis, including steep slopes, densely vegetated areas, and significant topographic elevation changes. The latter introduces strong topography dependent phase variations due to temporal changes in atmospheric temperature and/or pressure profiles (Figure S1), as observed in other islands of the Canary Islands archipelago [e.g., González et al., 2010]. To compensate for this effect, we applied a commonly used strategy based on an empirical polynomial relationship between atmospheric phase noise and topography. We noted that a simple linear model is insufficient to remove most of the atmospheric signal, a result that is in agreement with the nonlinear relationships necessary to model stratified troposphere signals [Doin et al., 2009]. Accordingly, we iteratively increased the polynomial degree of the model up to 4. We selected an area assumed to be less affected by deformation, in the northeastern portion of the island, to fit the data. To accept the optimal model, at each iteration, we computed an F statistic ratio to test the significance of the decrease in misfit, χ2, between the two successive models [Stein and Gordon, 1984]. Another significant disturbance is related to the imperfect knowledge of the satellite tracks. In this case, first-order artifacts can be compensated for by removing a linear or a quadratic ramp in both azimuth and range image directions [Pepe et al., 2011]. Therefore, before interpretation, each interferogram was corrected for orbital effects and atmospheric artifacts. This operation is critical because these disturbances can bias the geophysical interpretation if attributed to deformation signal. Examples of the original, modeled, and residual interferograms are shown in Figure S1.

[14] After the correction, most of interferograms did not show large signals for most of the analyzed period (e.g., see the RADARSAT-2 interferogram in Figure 4a). However, clear and intense deformation is detected in all interferograms spanning May 2011 to November 2011. Figures 4b–4e illustrates some of the interferograms with clear deformation patterns. Between 5 May 2011 and 8 August 2011, deformation observed with a RADARSAT-2 ascending track indicates a circular pattern of deformation in the center of the island, with a maximum of ~10 cm of motion toward the satellite, south of Tanganasoga volcano (Figure 4b). In a subsequent period, Figure 4c displays the deformation (maximum ~10 cm toward the satellite) from a descending ENVISAT interferogram spanning the entire month of September and a few weeks after the eruption started (31 August 2011 to 30 October 2011). The intense deformation pattern is indicative of an expansion source located offshore at Mar de Las Calmas. A slightly noisy descending CSK interferogram spanning 12 days before the beginning of the eruption shows that most of the observed deformation in Figure 4c occurred during September (Figure 4d). In Figure 4e, an independent ascending interferogram (RADARSAT-2 S7) confirms the two areas of deformation, a wide deformation centered in the island and a more intense and shorter wavelength deformation located at northwest of the Mar de las Calmas. Finally, slight inflation (motion toward the satellite) can be distinguished in a few interferograms spanning the November 2011 period (e.g., the ENVISAT interferogram in Figure 4f).

4 Modeling: Magma Plumbing System and Its Temporal Evolution

[15] To analyze the large wealth of computed interferograms, we propose a two-step approach with the aim of retrieving the temporal evolution of the ground deformation that is consistent between the different look angles and satellite sensors. First, we determine the active sources during the two seismically distinctive stages (pseudo-stationary in July-August and southeast migration in September and early October). We use those interferograms spanning the shortest time in order to constrain the best-fitting static displacements using simple elastic dislocation models. We perform a nonlinear inversion of the interferograms spanning the period May 2011 to October 2011. Once the static model is determined, a quasi-dynamic time-dependent model using a Green's function linear inversion scheme was employed to infer the variation of the source volume at each interferogram, which subsequently were used to solve for the sources evolution.

Static Model: Parameter Estimation

[16] We searched for the optimal model parameters of a few elastic models with simple geometries: spherical point source [Mogi, 1958], horizontal circular crack [Sun, 1969], ellipsoid source [Yang et al., 1988], and rectangular crack [Okada, 1985]. We included the effect of the topography by using the approximate method of Williams and Wadge [1998]. We adopted a nonlinear global inversion technique, bounded simulated annealing, to calculate the best-fitting model that finds the minima of the misfit function in a least squares sense [González et al., 2010]. All the interferograms were downsampled using a quadtree scheme [Jónsson et al., 2002] to reduce the computational burden while preserving the observed deformation patterns. To avoid solutions trapped in local minima, we restarted the nonlinear inversion 250 times with a homogeneously distributed random set of initial model parameters, with the same bounding limits as the model parameters. We improved the method presented in González et al. [2010] by introducing realistic noise at each iteration [Wright et al., 2003]. We simulated the random noise using an exponential and cosine theoretical covariance function,
(1)
where r is the distance between data points, σ2 is the noise variance (we assume σ2 = 4 cm2) and, a and b are the coefficients which control the correlation lag (here a = b = 0.05). Due to the small area of the studied region, we could not estimate correlation parameters for the interferograms which show deformation. Therefore, we assumed values that produce spatially correlated signals similar to the observed interferograms before the onset of seismicity. Finally, we determined the best-fitting model parameters as the mean of the 250 best-fitting set of modeled parameters and the associated errors as their standard deviations.

[17] In accordance with the seismicity evolution (Figures 2 and 3), we selected two interferograms spanning short times over the intense periods of seismicity and deformation. The selection of the specific interferograms was based on the possible sensitivity to different and independent sources corresponding to the observed different seismicity and deformation patterns (Figures 3 and 4). In particular, we chose one associated with the pseudo-stationary period during July and August (Figure 5a, covering the period 4 May 2011 to 8 August 2011), and another from the period during which seismicity migrated south-to-southeastward (Figure 5d, for the period 31 August 2011 to 30 October 2011). Solutions using the rectangular crack and ellipsoidal models were poorly constrained displaying a very large dispersion of the set (250) of optimal best-fitting parameters. We discarded those models because the model parameters had large uncertainties, on the same order of magnitude as the prescribed search bounding limits, and a clear indication of poor resolution. A circular horizontal crack and the spherical (Mogi) models provide essentially the same results (Figure S2). However, in the case of the circular crack, the source was generally slightly deeper than the spherical source (Table 1). Although the location is well determined, the volume change was poorly resolved. Therefore, we preferred the spherical source results (Table 1) because it is the simplest model that explains the signal up to the noise levels.

[18] In Figure 5, we show observed (Figures 5a and 5d), modeled (Figures 5b and 5e), and residual (Figures 5c and 5f) LOS displacement for the best-fitting spherical sources for the two interferograms spanning the selected periods. It is noteworthy that even with a very simple model, the spherical source, the data fit is acceptable for the ascending 4 May 2011 to 8 August 2011 interferogram (Figure 5c), despite some small residuals near the coastlines. In addition, we confirm the spherical best-fitting parameter results for the first period by repeating the inversion process using a stack of four observed RADARSAT-2 ascending differential interferograms with the 8 August 2011 as the common slave image (Table 1 and Figure S2). For the August to early October period, a spherical model is also a good approximation, as indicated by the fit to the descending 31 August 2011 to 30 October 2011 interferogram. However, small magnitude residuals along the Mar de las Calmas coastline (Figure 5f) may reflect a slightly asymmetric causative source, with an axis along the south rift direction (NNW-SSE). Considering these results, we subsequently assume the existence of two spherical magma reservoirs consistent with elastic model point sources which change in volume over time. The results constrain a static image of the magmatic system composed of two spherical point sources: a deeper reservoir at ~9.5 km and a shallower at ~4.5 km depth (Figure 5g).

Tracking Transient Source Volume Changes

4.2.1 Volume Changes Over Temporal Intervals

[19] Once a magmatic system of two spherical point sources was fixed, we performed a linear inversion of all 63 available interferograms in order to estimate for volume changes of the sources over the corresponding time interval. Ascending and descending interferograms from COSMO-SkyMed data acquired on the same day (Tables S1 and S2 in the supporting information) were jointly inverted. For each interferogram, we independently solved a forward problem of the type: d = G m, where d is the data vector (InSAR LOS observations), m is the model parameters vector (volume changes), and G is the Green's function matrix (source impulse response projected into the satellite LOS). The problem is solved using a bounded least squares method. We allowed for a variation of the estimated volume change between 0.10 and −0.05 km3, which are reasonable bounds considering the results of the nonlinear inversion presented in the previous section. As a result, we resolved for the source volume changes on both sources.

4.2.2 Source Volume Changes: Temporal Inversion

[20] The problem of retrieving time series of the source volume changes from nonsimultaneous and temporally overlapped multisensor observations is an ill-posed problem. This problem can be solved using regularization methods, e.g., first-order Tikhonov regularization [Grandin et al., 2010]. We consider a system of n increments of source volume changes (δqij) between two epochs ti and tj, where ti < tj, based on the linear inversion estimation of the corresponding interferograms. We want to solve for the temporal evolution of volume change for each observed epoch t ∈ [t0,…, tm], where m is the number of SAR acquisitions. In matrix notation, the problem can be formalized as the inversion of the linear system δq = A Q, where A is the differential operator (i.e., the incidence matrix, with −1 and 1 for master and slaves dates, respectively), δq is the known vector of increments of volume change (1 × n), and Q is the unknown vector of temporal volume change (1 × m). A trivial solution to this problem, even in the least squares sense (generalized inverse), is not possible because the interferograms are formed by data from different tracks and satellites, and therefore, not all acquisitions can be connected to each other. As a result, the linear system is formed by independent linear subsystems, making the problem underdetermined.

[21] One way to solve this problem is to search for the least squares solution imposing an additional minimum norm condition (minimum volume); this can be accomplished through the use of the Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) method. However, direct application of this strategy provides unrealistic results with large discontinuities in the time series.

[22] Similar to the approach of the Small Baseline Subset (SBAS) technique, which is designed to recover the time series of displacements from a subset of disconnected interferograms [Berardino et al., 2002], we reformulate the problem by minimizing the rate of the source volume changes, instead of the volume variation itself. This avoids the presence of large discontinuities in the final solution, which is retrieved after a final integration step, because the minimum norm constraint implies minimizing the overall rate of volume change rates instead of the volume change itself, which is a more physically sound constraint. Furthermore, to prevent possible oscillation in the solution, we consider a Truncated Singular Value Decomposition (TSVD) approach [Aster et al., 2005].

[23] According to the outlined strategy, we transformed the differential increments of volume change into rates considering the time spanned by each interferogram, q = δq / tij. We solved for the vector of rates of volume change between each available epoch, Q, a vector 1 × (m − 1), where the underline denotes rates. The new system of equations is organized as follows,

[27] In Figure 6, we show temporal evolution of the volume change for the considered sources (two spherical sources), obtained as described above, for the pre-eruptive and eruptive periods (the solution for the entire period, December 2009 to March 2012 is shown in Figure S4 of the supporting information). Those areas with significant residuals may reflect atmospheric noise in the corresponding interferograms, activity on other structures (e.g., shallow faults), a possible unaccounted eruptive conduit (e.g., see Figure 7c or 7d) or departures from the assumed source geometries that were not included in our simplified model.

5 Discussion

Active Shallow Magmatic System During the 2011–2012 El Hierro Eruption

[28] A simple model (Figure 5g) with two active sources accounts for the vigorous motions toward the satellite (uplift) observed before the onset of the submarine eruption (Figure 4). Two major difficulties arise from the use of such a simple elastic model: the elasticity assumption that is used to interpret all the observed ground deformation InSAR data, and the limited extension of the imaged area. Due to uncertainties in the rheological structure beneath El Hierro Island, we limit our discussion to crustal depths, where the rocks’ elastic behavior is commonly assumed. In the case of the Canary Islands, Moho depths have been estimated to be approximately 10–18 km [Banda et al., 1981; Ranero et al., 1995; Lodge et al., 2012]. The latter limitation reduces the resolvability to sources as a function of depth. In particular, sources deeper than the island's width will be difficult to detect because InSAR results are sensitive only to horizontal gradients of the projected LOS motion, which are stronger for shallow sources than deeper sources.

[29] InSAR results confirm that there was no slow precursory deformation signal before May 2011. Therefore, most, if not all, of the deformation should have started with the initial onset of the seismicity in 17 July. Between 4 May and 8 August 2011 a batch of magma with an estimated volume of 0.028 ± 0.003 km3 intruded at the base of the oceanic crust (crustal-mantle reservoir, CMR), at a depth of 9.5 ± 4 km. This is a depth consistent with the upper bounds of the hypocentral depths (8–15 km) of the reported seismicity for this period. This depth is also consistent with an intrusion stalled at the base of the oceanic crust, and likely not below it. The oceanic crust-mantle (moho) boundary at the Canary Islands indicates a gentle deepening toward the western Islands [Banda et al., 1981]. In particular, around El Hierro, it has been estimated at about 12–15 km using gravity and seismic reflection data [Ranero et al., 1995, Figure 7]. This batch of magma was located south of the main seismic locus (Figure 5g) and directly beneath the central part of the Island, not to the north [López et al., 2012; Martí et al., 2013]. This southern location is consistent with a nearly ~ N45E azimuth GPS velocity vector of the public FRON GPS station. GPS data are inconsistent with a more northern location, as suggested by the located seismicity (Figures 3a–3b and density curves in Figure 5g). Magma located at the main locus of seismicity would have caused larger eastward, rather than northward motions. However, this behavior is not observed in the published GPS data.

[30] At this initial phase, the location of the magma pulse seems to correspond quite well with the inferred feeding system of the Tanganasoga volcano (4000 year B.P.). This volcano is the only polygenetic volcano in El Hierro Island, and the only area where it is common to produce crystal-rich (ankaramite) lavas [Carracedo et al., 2001; Manconi et al., 2009]. Those crystal-rich lavas are significantly denser than other El Hierro lavas, which indicate more primitive (deeper) extraction regions, and interpreted as the effect of upper mantle decompression due to the El Golfo flank collapse [Manconi et al., 2009]. This observation, coupled with the presence of a new batch of magma at the CMR in this location, would indicate that this central area may be the main feeding system for the entire El Hierro volcanism. Magmas would ascend further, erupting directly above or distributed into the three rift zones, depending on the physic-chemical conditions of the melt or its overpressure (gas content).

[31] Between 8 August and 31 August 2011, our modeling results indicate the emplacement of an additional magma volume of about 0.015 km3 into the CMR. The influx volume magma rate apparently doubled (Figure 6). Although the increase in rate is not well constrained due to the low temporal SAR data resolution during this period, the apparent increase in the magma volume change time series is in accordance with an observed increase in low-magnitude seismicity rates, which by middle August peaked >400 events/day (Figure 2c). That increase in seismicity rate was not associated with a significant increment in the magnitude of the seismic events. However, the estimated magma influx and observed daily seismicity rates were the largest for the entire analyzed period. Simultaneously, between 10 and 17 August, a station located in the central part of the island detected a sharp increase in the diffuse degassing efflux of CO2 [Pérez et al., 2012]. Basaltic magma rising through a plumbing system saturates in CO2 at pressures corresponding to about 30 km depth, then buoyant CO2-rich gas exsolves and can rise rapidly to the surface [Gerlach et al., 2002]. It is worth noting that CO2 levels were at low levels in late July and early August. This might be explained by the fact that CO2 is highly soluble in the waters of shallow aquifers. Therefore, it is possible that the sudden increase marked the full saturation in CO2 due to an increase in deep influx. After this, the levels of CO2 efflux and 222Rn activity rates steadily increased during September until the eruption in early October [Pérez et al., 2012; Padilla et al., 2013].

[32] In September, the CMR did not change significantly in magma volume. This correlates with the gradual decrease in daily seismicity rates occurred until middle September. Since middle September 2011, GPS stations located in the north of the island started to indicate a more north-south deformation, with a slightly increase in daily deformation rates [López et al., 2012]. Seismicity began to spread southward, and hypocenters were located between 12 and 17 km depth (deeper than in the previous period). The N-S clustering of the seismicity may suggest the propagation of dikes; however, the surface deformation does not confirm it. In fact, the deepening of the events could be an artifact, reflecting that the southern part of the island is significantly more heterogeneous than the assumed 1-D crustal-mantle seismic layered model [López et al., 2012], as indicated by the large horizontal and depth reported errors in the seismic catalog (http://www.ign.es/ign/layoutIn/sismoFormularioCatalogo.do, note that mean horizontal xy error ellipse in Figure 2a and mean depth error bar in Figure 2b). Therefore, hypocenter location information should be interpreted carefully, at least for those events that occurred offshore, where the network configuration provides a poorer resolution. Nevertheless, these observations suggest that magma migrated laterally away from the central CMR for a distance of about 10 km. A possible reason for the migration could be the increase of magma overpressure due to expansion/exsolution of CO2, as it might indicated by the increments in diffuse gases detected in the central part of the island [Pérez et al., 2012].

[33] During September, the lack of dense temporal InSAR observations limits our ability to track accurately the magma migration, particularly with depth. Modeling of the interferograms spanning September 2011 did not support the existence of near-vertical dikes. For example, the descending interferogram 31 August to 30 October 2011 (Figure 4b) could be modeled by a dike with a strike angle parallel to the south-southeast rift zone, but the location was either too far from the coast or deepening strongly inward toward the shore (not vertical). In addition, a vertical dike poorly explains the observed descending interferograms. In Figure 4d, a small LOS shortening signal south of the island might corresponds to the opening of the submarine fissure eruption feeding the dike between 30 September and 12 October. However, the data do not allow for a reliable estimate of the causative source. As described previously, spherical or sill geometry better explains the InSAR observations (Table 1 and Figures 5d–5f). In particular, interferograms modeling supports a shallower and smaller magmatic reservoir located slightly offshore at the Mar de las Calmas coastline and at 4.5 ± 2 km depth. The depth of this reservoir, hereafter SFR, corresponds to the interface between the top of the oceanic crust, pre-volcanic sediments, and the volcanic edifice. The thickness of the pre-volcanic oceanic sediments has been estimated to be at least 1 km thick [Ranero et al., 1995]. This interface would generate a sufficient density/rheology contrast to trap the ascending magmas. Geodetic modeling results points to an increase in magma volume of about 0.01 km3 (Figures 6 and 7b). The SFR intruded magma volume emplaced at some time between 30 August and 31 September 2011.

[34] Cumulate geometric moment exhibited a steady state increase, primarily due to events occurring in the crust (Figure 2b and blue curve in Figure 6). During 23–27 September, the cumulative geometric moment exceeded ~5 m3 (Figure 2b), a value which seems to be a critical threshold value during this crisis (gray and blue curves in Figure 6). After 23–27 September (the last week of September and early October), seismicity began to be located around the Mar de las Calmas (Figures 3c and 3d). Cumulative geometric moment increased dramatically together with the event magnitudes, with up to 90 being felt by the population [Martí et al., 2013]. We suggest that this could mark the moment when the magma started to migrate and accumulate at the shallower SFR. Furthermore, this upward migration provides a reasonable explanation for a positive anomaly in differential geomagnetic signals that lasted for 3 days at this period. This was the only anomaly registered between September and end of October 2011 [López et al., 2012, Figure 4]. In addition, a mechanical loading model proposed to explain the magma migration predicts that far from the load (the center of the island), magma should emplace at shallower depths [Martí et al., 2013]. In fact, the numerical model parameterization indicates that magma should be trapped at about 3–5 km or deeper, at distances of 10 to 20 km from the load axis.

[35] Between 30 September and 12 October, seismicity remained high, but we did not detect significant changes in magma volumes at CMR or SFR. The largest event in that period occurred on 8 October at 20:35 UTC. The relatively large magnitude of this event allowed for calculating its focal mechanism parameters. Moment tensor waveforms inversion initially indicated 6 km depth (www.ign.es, accessed 28 March 2012). This event has been interpreted as the start of the upward migration of the magma toward the eruptive vents [Carracedo et al., 2012; López et al., 2012; Martí et al., 2013]. The shallow moment centroid depth (~6 km) seems to be consistent with our estimate for the SFR and realistically could have opened a path for the migration of magma toward the surface. The surface rupture involved in a Mw4.0 corresponds to an area of approximately ~500 × 500 m2 with a few centimeters of slip, probably too small to open a significant path at ~12 km depth for magma upward migration. In addition, a shallower reservoir could explain the observed high levels and gradual increase in H2S efflux recorded at a station located on the Mar de las Calmas coastline prior to the submarine eruption [Pérez et al., 2012]. In 7 October (installation date), this station recorded H2S efflux values about twice as high as the levels after the eruption began, when H2S efflux stabilized to assumed background levels. Hydrogen sulfide separates only from the parental magmas at hydrothermal conditions (low lithostatic pressures). Conversely, Pérez et al. [2012] reported the absence of anomalous H2S efflux at the center of the island. It supports the conclusion that magma at a depth of 10–15 km could not exsolve that sulfur species in measurable quantities at the surface. Therefore, this indicates that the magma was already at shallow depths in 7 October, at least a day before the 8 October earthquake.

[36] We favor the hypothesis that magma started to migrate upward and accumulate at the SFR in 26–27 September, and for the next 2 weeks, the reservoir pressurized. The pressurization culminated with the 8 October 2011 event. Then, for approximately 32 h, the magma migrated laterally in the topographically down-rift direction for ~5 km. During this period, very mild and shallow (1 to 6 km depth) seismicity occurred [www.ign.es]. This period ended with the emergence of a growing amplitude tremor signal (10 October 2012, ~4:15 UTC). Tremor amplitude increased for about 58 h when the signal abruptly ceased after a peak in high frequencies at 14:30 UTC on 12 October 2011. During the next 24 h, several additional high frequency peaks were recorded. We interpret this as the magma started to ascend vertically on the 10 October 2012, ~4:15 UTC. Tremor increased in amplitude as the magma was ascending and decompression of vesicularized magmatic gasses or interaction with groundwater was amplified, as commonly observed in other volcanoes [McNutt, 1996; Patanè et al., 2008]. The sudden decrease in tremor amplitude provides a good indication of the initial/explosive opening of the submarine vent. Therefore, the start of the submarine eruption occurred on 12 October 2012, when the first clear pale color water plume was observed. Subsequent, high frequency peaks in the tremor could be associated with submarine explosions. The temporal evolution suggests a final magma ascend rate of ~0.02–0.03 m/s. This much simpler interpretation accounts for the observations and contrasts with a previously proposed migration model based on a 3 km long rift backpropagation toward higher topography, from 1000 m to 300 below sea level depth [Martí et al., 2013], which, to date, is not supported by the published bathymetric surveys (http://www.ieo.es/hierro.htm). It also explains the absence or minor effects observed on the sea surface between the 10 and 12 October 2011 [López et al., 2012]. Some residuals in the modeled interferograms, limited to the very south edge of the island, could be related to the shallow conduit feeding the eruptive fissure (Figures 7c and 7d).

[37] On 15 October 2011, floating material appeared off La Restinga. The material varied from a mixture of mafic and white pumice to large basanite floating balloons [Troll et al., 2012; Carracedo et al., 2012]. Pérez-Torrado et al. [2012] attributed the latter to material commonly formed during shallow submarine eruptions, as observed during the La Serreta eruption in Faial, Azores Islands [Gaspar et al., 2003]. Basanite lava balloons were observed during the entire eruptive period. However, the first products called “restingolitas” or xenopumices appeared just during the first few days of the eruption. The xenopumices have been attributed as formed by three main processes: (a) partial melting and vesiculation of pre-island quartz-rich sedimentary rocks carried by the ascending magma [Troll et al., 2012], (b) remobilization of a stagnant phonolitic melt present as late differentiate in the crust and successive variable interaction with old oceanic crust and the volcanic edifice [Sigmarsson et al., 2012], and (c) the result of the thermally induced interaction between an ascending basanitic magma, a stagnant trachytic magma pocket/s, and an associated hydrothermally altered halo with rhyolitic composition [Meletlidis et al., 2012]. Indeed, the xenopumices interpretations could provide some clues on the migration of the magma. Petrological experiments (mineral assemblage, composition, and crystal content) carried out with xenopumice samples are compatible with an isobaric (P = 100 MPa, ~ 4 km) crystallization of trachytic melt cooling from 1035°C to 900°C [Meletlidis et al., 2012]. However, other analytical results of xenopumice incompatible trace elements, designed to distinguish different magmatic differentiation processes, are still controversial [Meletlidis et al., 2012; Troll et al., 2012]. It is interesting to note that all hypotheses for the generation of the xenopumices require magma stalled with different degrees and/or time residences, at shallow (~4 km) depth [Meletlidis et al., 2012; Troll et al., 2012; Sigmarsson et al., 2012], in agreement with a pre-island seafloor and volcanics interface. These observations further support a previously undetected shallow SFR reservoir.

[38] After the start of the eruption, the volume change at the deeper CMR started to decline, while the shallow reservoir, SFR, did not change significantly for the remainder of the study period, as confirmed by the absence of shallow depth cumulative geometric moment (blue curve in Figure 6). This decrease lasted until beginning of November 2011, when it ceased. The increment in magma volume seems to correlate with a period of seismic quiescence and the beginning (26 October 2011) of very deep (20–30 km) seismicity located in the north of the island (Figures 3d–3e). During this phase, earthquakes magnitude increased until to the occurrence of a mbLg 4.6 event on 8 November 2011. Just after the mbLg 4.6 earthquake, an increment in volume of approximately 0.01 km3 occurred at the CMR increase. The earthquake sequence could be the result of a collapse of the deeper segments of the magma plumbing system due to magma withdrawal and/or chamber walls relaxation [McNutt, 1996]. A geodetically undetected deeper reservoir or plexus of intertwined intrusions and sills at this depth range corresponds with petrologically constrained results [Stroncik et al., 2009]. The collapse of an ~25 km deep magma reservoir could favor a transient increase in magma ascent rate. Evidence for a new, less-degassed (more primitive) magma batch is supported by the significant increment of CO2 soil diffuse efflux surveys in November-December 2011 [Melián et al., 2012].

[39] In late December, visible sea surface discoloration disappeared. This might be related to the observed steady volume change decrease at the CMR in December (Figure 6). That clear trend stopped in early January when basaltic floating bombs reappeared and occurred discontinuously throughout February. Again, this observation agrees with a mild and not completely significant increase in volume change at the CMR reservoir. This also correlates with a modest increase in the detected daily seismicity rate (Figure 2c). During February and March, CMR volume change further decreased. By early March, the absence of visible effects on the sea surface and the lower levels of seismicity triggered the official declaration of the end of the eruption on 5 March 2012 [www.gobiernodecanarias.org/dgse/noticias_sismo_hierro.html]. The invariant (overpressure) volume change at the shallower rift flank reservoir, SFR, the behavior of the volume change in the CMR, and its relation to the visible changes at the eruptive site is evidence for an active (magmatic) hydraulic connection between the deep plumbing system and the eruptive vent. We illustrate a conceptual model of the entire eruption in Figure 8.

[40] These results, derived from the geodetic data of the 2011–2012 eruption, support a mechanical scenario beneath the El Hierro Island which is quite similar to that proposed for the Island of Hawaii [Ryan, 1993]. A central magmatic plumbing system focus magma (dikes) ascent, which propagates from the mantle upward due to buoyancy forces until it reaches a horizon of neutral buoyancy [Tilling and Dvorak, 1993], the oceanic crust. Then, depending of the relative magma overpressure (e.g., gas content), new and/or evolved magmas might be distributed into the rift zones or continued along a vertical ascent path. Therefore, at least two horizons of neutral buoyancy would be present at El Hierro. A deep horizon associated with olivine-rich cumulates (main magma underplating region) exists at a depth of 6–10 km for Hawaii, or ~9.5 km at El Hierro (lower oceanic crust) and a shallower one at 2–4 km in Hawaii, or ~4.5 km at El Hierro. Magma accumulation occurs preferentially at or near those horizons, which facilitates lateral migration [Fialko and Rubin, 1998; Grandin et al., 2012] and possible eruption along rift zones.

Implications for the Active Magmatic Systems of Oceanic Island Volcanoes

[41] We obtain a detailed and complex image of the main magma storage locations. We track the magma migration before, during, and after the El Hierro 2011–2012 submarine eruption by combining data from different SAR sensors. Geodetic data and modeling results, coupled with independent observations (e.g., gas emissions, loading mechanical models, and geochemistry and petrology of erupted material) from this eruption revealed its crustal magmatic plumbing system. Our results for the El Hierro eruption indicate two levels of magma stagnation that persist for a minimum of weeks to months at the base of the oceanic crust (~9.5 km), and at least days to weeks at the paleo-oceanic seafloor (~4 km).

[42] Evidence presented here is in contrast with previous magma plumbing systems models (depths) based solely on petrological analysis of Canary Islands lavas. Petrology evidence shows very short-term magma stagnations of, at most, few days at shallow crustal levels [Kluegel et al., 2005]. Most studies systematically indicate magmatic systems with main storage volumes at mantle pressures of 600–1400 MPa or ~15–45 km depth [Kluegel et al., 2005; Longpré et al., 2008; Stroncik et al., 2009]. However, Kluegel et al. [2005] also identified a bimodal distribution of pressures based on the analysis of phenocrystals and fluid inclusions at La Palma, with fluid inclusions indicative of shallower depths (7–14 km). They concluded that fluid inclusions reequilibrate faster than the growth of phenocrystal rims at equilibrium conditions. The same bimodality has been observed at Fogo Island [Hildner et al., 2012]. Based on the considerations of typical reequilibration times of phenocrystals and fluid inclusions, it excluded shallower magma stagnation before eruptions with residence times longer than hours to days [Kluegel et al., 2005; Longpré et al., 2008]. Therefore, our deeper inferred depth range (~9.5 km) for the active magmatic reservoirs during the El Hierro eruptions is consistent with depths estimated from fluid inclusions analysis for oceanic island volcanoes [Kluegel et al., 2005; Hildner et al., 2012]. However, our results indicate residence times at this depth range that are significantly longer than the previously suggested hours to days.

[43] Regarding the shallowest level of magma stagnation at El Hierro (~4.5 km), at least two of the proposed hypotheses for the origin of the xenopumices imply the existence of shallow reservoirs with trachitic magmas evolving to phonolitic compositions [Sigmarsson et al., 2012], or long-lasting rhyolitic alteration halo surrounding a hot shallow trachitic magma pocket [Meletlidis et al., 2012]. Additionally, evidence for the relevance of this depth range for the Canary Islands can be found from the analysis of other volcanoes. In Gran Canaria, estimated pressure in fluid inclusion samples indicate reservoirs at 2–4 km depth, which are interpreted as a relevant horizon of neutral buoyancy [Hansteen et al., 1998]. The analysis of fluid inclusion pressures of Gran Canaria samples is relevant because those are from eruptive products in its shield basalt stage, the current oceanic island volcano evolution stage for El Hierro. A similar magma depth has been estimated for Tenerife Island (Canary Islands) during a more evolved stage (central subplinian volcanism). Recently, a magma storage depth was inferred at about 5 ± 1 km beneath the summit of Teide volcano using phase equilibrium experiments [Andújar et al., 2010]. In addition, P wave seismic velocity contrast horizons at ~4 km depth have been found for La Palma, Tenerife, and Lanzarote [Lodge et al., 2012]. This suggests that this depth range may represent a regional horizon of neutral buoyancy for the Canary Islands magmas. It clearly corresponds to the average pre-island seafloor with a variable effect due to lithospheric flexural volcanic loading. Such magma stagnation levels can be interpreted as an initial stage in the formation of magma chambers, similar to those actually present in other, more evolved, Canary Islands oceanic island volcanoes such as at Tenerife and Gran Canaria [Ablay and Martí, 2000]. When magma chambers establish, primitive melts can fractionate to generate evolved magmas (e.g., phonolites) that could reach eruptable conditions similar to the central Canary Islands. However, at least for the current stage of volcanic evolution, we find that those conditions are not met in the El Hierro magmatic plumbing system.

[44] At the current shield-building stage in El Hierro, we also cannot rule out that the detected reservoirs may be more ephemeral and solidify completely at depth, thus confirming part of the proposed active magmatic underplating beneath Canary Islands volcanoes [Dañobeitia and Canales, 2000; Lodge et al., 2012]. Thus, the magmatic underplating process could explain the observed rates of island uplift, as seen, e.g., at La Palma [Staudigel and Schmincke, 1984; Hildenbrand et al., 2003] and Tenerife [Kroechert et al., 2008]. Since the end of the eruption, several episodes of renewed seismicity occurred in June-July 2011, September 2011, and December 2011 to January 2012 (www.ign.es). Those seismic swarms, all deeper than 10 km, were accompanied with clear uplift signals at the IGN and INVOLCAN GPS monitoring networks [www.ign.es; Sagiya et al., 2012]. Each post-eruption seismic swarm distributed over areas that were not affected by previous seismicity during the pre-eruption and coeruption periods. In general, the seismo-deformation swarm patterns indicate that magmatic underplating contributes to a relatively homogeneous uplifting of the entire volcanic edifice (island). The observed episode at El Hierro suggests that the magma plumbing system and underplating process could have significant differences among islands. For example, at La Palma, a strong asymmetry affects the uplifted formations (seamount), which are tilted toward the west [Staudigel and Schmincke, 1984], which may partially explain observed azimuth differences in P-to-S receiver functions beneath this island [Li et al., 2003]. These results are unexpected and reveal substantial differences in the magmatic plumbing systems among the Canary Islands chain. Here, we speculate that differences in the distribution of magmatic underplating and the relative importance of the shallowest horizon of neutral buoyancy may result in the development of central phonolitic volcanic systems in some islands, e.g., Tenerife and Gran Canaria, and the absence in other islands, e.g., Lanzarote, Fuerteventura, La Gomera, and perhaps La Palma.

[45] Studies of the magma plumbing systems at (basaltic) oceanic island volcanoes have revealed fundamental differences in their shallower (crustal) levels (e.g., Reunion, Galápagos, Hawaiian, Canarian, and Cape Verde Islands). Shallow (crustal) magma chambers have been postulated but they are not always present or detected. At Hawaii, magma chambers stagnate and distribute magma along elongated rift zones [Tilling and Dvorak, 1993]. At Tenerife and Gran Canaria Islands, crustal magma chambers develop as long-lived features able to fractionate parental basanitic composition melts into end-member (highly explosive) phonolitic magmas [Ablay and Martí, 2000]. Our results indicate two active crustal magma reservoirs at ~9.5 and ~4.5 km for the 2011–2012 El Hierro eruption. Interestingly, volcanic systems with two crustal magma accumulation levels are relatively common for a number of oceanic island volcanoes. For example, in the Island of Hawaii, the central feeding system of Kilauea volcano is composed of main two main levels of magma storage, in particular at about 1 km and about 3 km depth [Cervelli and Miklius, 2003; Baker and Amelung, 2012]. Two active magmatic chambers have been detected in the last 30 years at La Piton de la Fournaise, at ~2.5 and ~7 km [Peltier et al., 2009]. At the Galápagos Islands, active shallow crustal magma reservoirs have been detected geodetically at Wolf, Darwin, Alcedo, Cerro Azul, and Sierra Negra volcanoes. However, only at Fernandina Island volcano has two levels of magma storage been reliably estimated at depths of ~1 and ~5 km [Chadwick et al., 2011; Bagnardi and Amelung, 2012]. As it seems a common feature, we can designate this two-level magma crustal storage system in oceanic island volcanoes as a doublet crustal magmatic system.

[46] The existence of shallow crustal magmatic systems has been previously attributed to relative importance of the deep mantle magma melt supply rates [Clague and Dixon, 2000]. Our results indicate that the high melt supply is not a sufficient condition for the existence of the shallow magma reservoirs, because the Canary Islands has one of the lowest magma supply rates for oceanic island volcanoes, ~0.0002 km3/yr [Amelung and Day, 2002]. Other conditions have been proposed to explain the existence or not of crustal magmatic chambers. Hildner et al. [2012] proposed that the age of the underlying lithosphere could control this behavior. In Figure 9, we show the relation between age of the underlying lithosphere and the depth of crustal magma chambers (constrained using geodetic data, under relatively similar assumptions). The figure illustrates a weak trend from shallower systems to deeper ones, as oceanic lithosphere ages. However, an anomaly occurs in the case of the crustal magmatic system from Hawaiian volcanoes, which are resting on a ~90 Ma old oceanic lithosphere. The active Hawaiian magmatic systems are significantly shallower than the one expected for an age progression. If we consider mid- to long-term magma supply rates, a clearer trend is observed (Figure 10). Both the shallowest and deepest reservoirs in single and doublet systems are deeper when the magma supply rate is lower. This result illustrates that the main controlling factor is the thermomechanical structure of the crust, which depends strongly on the deep mantle magma supply rate, and also on the age of the oceanic lithosphere. This occurs because older oceanic lithospheres are significantly cooler than younger and buoyant oceanic crust (lithosphere), causing the seafloor to deepen due to thermal contraction and increase in density.

[47] The observation that there is a pervasive absence of reservoirs at the shallow crustal levels at some oceanic islands needs to be revised [Amelung and Day, 2002; Kluegel et al., 2005]. The lack of shallow magmatic systems may be attributed to fairly local processes that sometimes can significantly disturb their structure, such as catastrophic flank collapses [Amelung and Day, 2002; Manconi et al., 2009]. On the other hand, it might be a sampling artifact, because many volcanoes lack sufficient or good quality data over the typical long-recurrence eruptive periods, in particular for oceanic island volcanoes with modest magma supply rates (e.g., Azores, Canary Islands, Cape Verde, or Comoros).

6 Conclusions

[48] We successfully combined multifrequency and multisatellite interferometric data to study the volcanic deformation associated with the 2011–2012 El Hierro submarine eruption, with a temporal sampling of ~10 days during the eruption. This study demonstrates the potential to obtain high-resolution temporal deformation and mitigate poor geodetic volcano monitoring systems using a combination of spaceborne radar satellites. In addition, our results also demonstrate the applicability of radar observations to studying offshore eruptions, if occurring close to the coast. In the near future, the next generation of radar satellites, such as the satellite constellations COSMO-SkyMed and the planned RADARSAT Constellation Mission, and short revisit time missions such as ESA Sentinel-1 and the Japanese ALOS-2, will allow the study of subweekly to daily magma volume changes in land volcanic systems at a global scale.

[49] This data processing and modeling approach allows us to analyze the full range of temporal changes of the magmatic sources that produce the observed deformation (Figure 8). The interpretation of the results provides evidence for two reservoirs, CMR, larger and ~9.5 km depth, and SFR, a smaller offshore rift elongated at ~4.5 km depth. This dense temporal sampling suggests magma started to accumulate in the center of the island for about 2 months, migrated southward, and ascended to about 4 km depth in late September. Finally, lateral and vertical migration occurred between 9 and 12 October 2012. Starting on the 12 October 2012 and continuing for the subsequent 5 months, magma erupted along a submarine NW-SE fissure vent(s) without significant fissure migration. Volume changes in the CMR are consistent with the ascent of one or two more primitive magma pulses from an upper mantle (deeper) source during November 2011 and January-February 2012. The latter batches of magma contributed to the relatively long eruption duration (~5 months), as compared to previous shorter Canary Islands eruptions.

[50] The detection/existence of a very shallow magmatic reservoir has important implications in the understanding of the Canary Islands volcanoes crustal magma plumbing systems. We conclude that the existence of shallow reservoirs, active for relatively long periods of time (at least weeks to months) might suggest initial stages of magma chamber formation. Shallow magmatic reservoirs could fractionate primitive basanitic magmas into evolved trachites or phonolite, as erupted in La Palma and more voluminously in Tenerife and Gran Canaria. Such magmas could reach eruptable conditions as the magmatic system that feed the oceanic island volcano evolves to a more mature evolutionary stage at least for the western Canary Islands. However, at El Hierro, those conditions do not meet the current stage of volcanic evolution. In addition, magma stagnated at or near the crustal-mantle reservoir(s) may contribute to the deep cumulitic complexes. Cumulitic complexes are common at oceanic island volcanoes and have been detected using geophysical surveys. The complete solidification of magma would correspond to an active magmatic underplating beneath Canary Islands volcanoes. Spatial variability of magmatic underplating could explain the observed rates of island uplift and patterns, as observed at La Palma and Tenerife Islands.

[51] Geodetic interpretation of the deformation associated with the 2011–2012 eruption revealed that the crustal magma plumbing system of the Canary Islands oceanic island volcanoes are relatively similar to other oceanic volcano groups (Hawaii, Piton de la Fournaise, and Galápagos). In particular, doublet magma storage levels seem to be a recurrent feature in many oceanic island volcanoes. Lack of shallow crustal magma chambers (e.g., El Hierro) has been suggested for low-magma supply rate volcanic areas. This could lead to artifacts resulting from the low activity and long-recurrence time of eruptions. However, local catastrophic events might sometimes disturb the shallow magmatic system, e.g., Fogo Island. Data from El Hierro shallow magmatic system suggest that the existence and depth of crustal magma chambers can be attributed to the thermomechanical conditions of the oceanic lithosphere on which the volcanic islands rest. Such thermomechanical conditions would depend strongly on the mantle magma supply rate and on the age of the oceanic lithosphere.
